10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Who is a company for?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most interesting theoretical problem in co=
rporate governance today is, if you are the chief executive officer of a pu=
blic company, should you try to maximize=C2=A0<em>the value of your company=
=E2=80=99s stock</em>, or should you try to maximize=C2=A0<em>the value of =
your stockholders=E2=80=99 portfolios</em>? I guess you could do other thin=
gs too, but the popular model these days is that your job is to maximize sh=
areholder value. One way to maximize value for your shareholders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the traditional way =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to make your company=E2=80=99s =
stock go up. The other way to maximize value for your shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the modern-portfolio-theory way =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to make all of t=
he=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>stocks that your shareholders=C2=A0<em>also=C2=
=A0</em>own go up.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody really says that, because it is insane.=
 For one thing, if you are the CEO of a public company, you don=E2=80=99t r=
eally=C2=A0<em>know=C2=A0</em>with precision what other stocks your shareho=
lders own, so it is hard to make them go up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0For another thing, if you are the CEO of a public company, you ha=
ve a significant ability to make your own company=E2=80=99s stock go up and=
 a limited ability to make other companies=E2=80=99 stocks go up: If you ar=
e a small oil-exploration company, and your shareholders=E2=80=99 biggest h=
olding is Apple Inc., realistically you are not going to move Apple=E2=80=
=99s stock price much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, =E2=80=9Cmaximize the value of=
 your stock=E2=80=9D provides a relatively concrete guide to action at a bu=
siness you control: You allocate capital well and do stuff to maximize cash=
 flows, and your stock goes up. It also just sort of makes sense as a busin=
ess proposition: The stuff that makes your stock go up in the long run is p=
retty much the stuff that makes your business successful; if your stock goe=
s up then in some broad crude sense you are probably doing some things righ=
t for your customers and employees and suppliers and community. =E2=80=9CMa=
ximize the value of your shareholders=E2=80=99 portfolio=E2=80=9D does not =
really provide CEOs a useful guide to action, and does not really make sens=
e for their businesses. Sometimes the best thing for the shareholders=E2=80=
=99 portfolio might be to shut down a viable company so a competitor can ma=
ke more money, and that feels like a bad business decision.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So when I say that this is the most interestin=
g theoretical problem in corporate governance, I do not really mean that CE=
Os wrestle with this problem, or that there are academic papers published o=
n both sides. Everyone agrees that =E2=80=9Cmaximize your stock value=E2=80=
=9D is right and =E2=80=9Cmaximize the value of your stockholders=E2=80=99 =
portfolios=E2=80=9D is bizarre.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s what makes it interesting! It b=
urbles beneath the surface; nobody <em>says </em>the insane answer, but it =
is subtly influential.=C2=A0It really is the case that a large percentage o=
f the shares of public companies are owned by large diversified institution=
al shareholders, including a lot of index funds and <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDItMDkvcXVhc2ktaW5kZXhlcnMtZ3Jvd3Ro=
LWFuZC1jb25mdXNpb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafe7961a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  quasi-index=C2=A0in=
vestors</a>, who care more about the overall value of their diversified por=
tfolios than they do about the stock price of any one company. It would be =
weird if corporate governance did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>respond to that ch=
ange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDQtMTYvc2hvdWxkLW11dHVhbC1mdW5kcy1iZS1pbGxl=
Z2FsLT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b5ab58e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked</a> a <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTItMDcvcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYt=
aW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWJhZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc23b8d8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  lot</a> over=
 the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.2564=
03/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDctMjIv=
aW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtbWF5LXdvcmstYS1saXR0bGUtdG9vLXdlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMjIzX01=
PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm=
09MjMwNjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB547ead9=
b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  years</a> about a theory that the rise of index ownership le=
ads to less product-market competition and higher prices: The idea is that =
softer competition and higher prices are good for an industry=E2=80=99s ove=
rall profits, so diversified shareholders who own all of the competitors in=
 an industry subtly or explicitly pressure them to compete less. No shareho=
lder or executive actually talks like this, but some academics claim to fin=
d some empirical evidence of its effects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And those large diversified investors=C2=A0<em=
>do=C2=A0</em>sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDQvZmFjZWJvb2std2hpc3RsZWJsb3dlci1zaG93cy1hLXNoaWZ0LWluLXNo=
YXJlaG9sZGVyLXZhbHVlcy1hd2F5LWZyb20tcHJvZml0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIyMjNfTU9ORVl=
TVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMz=
A2MjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfa1f4fa" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  talk about systemic factors</a> that affect all of the companies in=
 their portfolios. Most notably they talk about ESG, environmental, social =
and governance investing, which is in part a framework for big diversified =
investors to consider systemic risks and the externalities of their investm=
ents: If 1% of your portfolio is invested in oil and gas companies, and the=
y drill more oil and make more money, but as a result the earth gets warmer=
 and weather events wipe out the value of other companies that make up 10% =
of your portfolio, then that was bad, for you, financially. ESG is a way to=
 consider the systemic risks of your portfolio and pressure companies =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the oil companies=E2=80=94=C2=A0to mitigate those risks. =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjYvc3=
RhcnR1cHMtc29tZXRpbWVzLXN0cmV0Y2gtdGhlLXRydXRoP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjIyM19NT05FW=
VNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIz=
MDYyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd5d397c" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">
Systemic stewardship</a>,=E2=80=9D people sometimes call it, pushing indivi=
dual companies to reduce the systemic risks to your whole portfolio.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or during Covid-19 vaccine development we <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjQvdGhlLXZhY=
2NpbmUtaXMtbm90LWEtY29tcGV0aXRpb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIyJnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad1e733c" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talk=
ed</a> a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.=
256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjAtMDMt=
MTkvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtY3VyaW5nLWEtcGFuZGVtaWMtY291bGQtbWFrZS15b3UtcmljaD9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwNjIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBaec11afb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> bit</a> about how shareholders in biotech co=
mpanies working on vaccines had an economic interest in those vaccines that=
 <em>dwarfed=C2=A0</em>their economic interest in the shares of the compani=
es themselves. Widely available vaccines would reopen the global economy an=
d create enormous value for cruise operators and hotel companies and retail=
ers and airlines and office landlords and everybody else; even if the drug =
companies gave the vaccines away and bankrupted themselves, that would be g=
ood=C2=A0<em>for their shareholders</em>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I said above that nobody=C2=A0<em>says=
=C2=A0</em>that the duty of a public-company CEO is to maximize the value o=
f her stockholders=E2=80=99 portfolios, rather than the value of her own co=
mpany=E2=80=99s stock. But a few people do say it; they=E2=80=99re just wei=
rd. We have talked a few times about the Shareholder Commons, an activist g=
roup that submits shareholder proposals to public companies (<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTQvaXQtcGF5cy10by1ub3Q=
