FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7abc0cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Fox Corp., for insta=
nce</a>) asking them to focus less on their own profits and more on systemi=
c risk. And now here is an absolutely incredible (and <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVzaGFyZWh=
vbGRlcmNvbW1vbnMuY29tL3BvbGljeS1saXRpZ2F0aW9uLWxldHRlcnMv/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB99d17fbc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Shareholder Commons-related</a>)=C2=A0<em><a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J0bFozZ0c2VFJ=
YWS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5f7a174" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">lawsuit in Delaware Chan=
cery Court</a> </em>accusing Mark Zuckerberg, Sheryl Sandberg and other exe=
cutives and directors of Meta Platforms Inc. of=C2=A0<em>violating their fi=
duciary duties to shareholders=C2=A0</em>because they care too much about M=
eta and not enough about all the other stocks that the shareholders own:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a corporation whose impact is so widesprea=
d, the well-established doctrine of stockholder primacy cannot be rationall=
y applied on behalf of investors=C2=A0without recognizing the impact of por=
tfolio theory, which inextricably links common=C2=A0stock ownership to broa=
d portfolio diversification. The economic benefits from =E2=80=94 indeed th=
e viability of =E2=80=94 a system of corporate law rooted in maximizing fin=
ancial value for stockholders would vanish if it forced directors to make d=
ecisions that increased corporate value but depressed portfolio values for =
most of its stockholders. But this is precisely how the Company has operate=
d: Defendants have ignored the interests of all of its diversified stockhol=
ders, making decisions as if the costs that Meta imposes on such portfolios=
 were not meaningful to stockholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This circumstance is particularly troubling be=
cause it favors the small subset of stockholders who control the Company th=
rough the ownership of highly concentrated positions of high-voting common =
stock, including the Company=E2=80=99s CEO and Chairman. For this controlli=
ng subset, maximizing the value of the Company by undermining the global ec=
onomy is financially beneficial. This conflict is exacerbated by Company po=
licies that require all directors and high-ranking officers to own Company =
stock, as well as the granting of initial and annual awards of stock to all=
 directors and compensation policies that reward Company activities that be=
nefit the Company=E2=80=99s financial performance, regardless of the Compan=
y=E2=80=99s impact on the diversified portfolios of its stockholders.=C2=A0=
These fiduciaries have chosen to maximize the value that matters to them pe=
rsonally, rather than the financial values that matter to the Company=E2=80=
=99s diversified stockholder base. The Defendants=E2=80=99=C2=A0interests a=
re directly at odds with those of the diversified stockholders, who own onl=
y a minority voting stake due to the Company=E2=80=99s dual class capital s=
tructure.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, there is a conflict of interest betwe=
en Facebook=E2=80=99s executives and directors and its shareholders, becaus=
e the executives and directors=C2=A0<em>own too much Facebook stock</em>. I=
f they owned less Facebook stock and more stock in other companies, their i=
nterests would be more aligned with those of their other shareholders, and =
they=E2=80=99d manage Facebook for the benefit of the whole stock market ra=
ther than to maximize its own value. Facebook should pay its executives in =
S&amp;P 500 index funds, not in Facebook shares, is I guess the theory here=
.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is the opening of the complaint in the ca=
se, filed last October. In March, Meta <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bW=
VudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JFZ0JJc2Z5R0lxYy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB460605de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> moved to dismiss the case</a>, writing:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fiduciaries of Delaware corporations do no=
t owe a duty to oversee, consider, or protect a stockholder=E2=80=99s inves=
tments in other companies=E2=80=94their duties are to Meta and its stockhol=
ders in their capacity as stockholders of that company. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At bottom, Plaintiff is not pursuing claims un=
der the law as it exists, but rather using this case to broadcast his theor=
ies about how he would like the law to change. Tellingly, Plaintiff never e=
xplains how his preferred version of fiduciary duty law=C2=A0could feasibly=
 be followed=E2=80=94where the decisions of corporate fiduciaries must be g=
uided by not only what is in the best interests of the corporation itself, =
but also what is in the best interests of every other company, including Me=
ta=E2=80=99s competitors, or the =E2=80=9Cglobal economy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is quite right: The lawsuit is not so muc=
h a real lawsuit as it is a piece of performance art, or a philosophy paper=
. It doesn=E2=80=99t really provide a guide for corporate action; it is jus=
t an abstract inquiry into what the corporation is for. I=C2=A0love it so m=
uch. The plaintiff <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0=
hCRmRmeElVL3JKVEpjdGdrWmFBUS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd29e04f5" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> filed a response last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While fiduciaries have a general o=
bligation to maximize financial value, that obligation must end when it is =
opposed to stockholder interests. Accordingly, Defendants cannot refuse to =
consider whether increases in Meta=E2=80=99s financial value come from the =
pockets of typical Meta stockholders through harm to their investments. Jus=
t as <em>Revlon </em>prioritizes <em>stockholder </em>return over <em>corpo=
rate </em>cash flows in a sale, fiduciaries must make a good faith effort t=
o address the true cost of corporate operations that tax stockholders=E2=80=
=99 portfolios. Although Delaware courts=C2=A0may not have previously enfor=
ced this obligation, they have not rejected it either, and consistent appli=
cation of longstanding principles demands its recognition.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously a rule saying that corporate executi=
ves should maximize the value of their shareholders=E2=80=99 portfolios wou=
ld make no sense=C2=A0<em>for the company</em>. But it would arguably make =
sense=C2=A0<em>for the shareholders</em>, and aren=E2=80=99t they what matt=
ers?</p>
