<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Where does the value in financial services com=
e from? Some possibilities:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some people have extra money that they=
 want to invest; other people need money to do projects; connecting the peo=
ple who have money to the people who need money is valuable, and you can ge=
t paid for doing it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some people h=
ave risk and want to be safer; other people would like to take on a bit mor=
e risk to earn more money; finding good ways to slice risk and allocate it =
to the people who want it is valuable, and you can get paid for doing it.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Economic structures are also=C2=A0<=
em>legal=C2=A0</em>structures, and law and regulation allocate property rig=
hts. Finding ways to make the legal system allocate more property rights to=
 your clients (and away from people who are not your clients) is valuable, =
<em>to your clients</em>, and you can get paid for doing it.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine the relative value of these =
activities, and the amount of value you can capture by doing them, shifting=
 over time. When capital is scarce=C2=A0and communications are hard, knowin=
g where to find investors is a rare and valuable skill that you can charge =
a lot for. When capital is plentiful and the internet connects everyone and=
 anyone can raise $100 million in 10 minutes, your contacts with investors =
are less valuable.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjcvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtaXMtaW4tbGltYm8_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MDYyMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBbe76a95b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  talked a while back</a> about my career as a corpor=
ate equity derivatives banker. In some textbook economic sense, derivatives=
 are about risk allocation, but in my line of work, I wrote, =E2=80=9Cderiv=
atives were essentially about regulatory arbitrage=E2=80=9D: We did stuff t=
o optimize taxes or accounting, not to allocate risk more sensibly. I wrote=
:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lesson that I learned from my =
career as a derivatives structurer is that much of finance is about this so=
rt of regulatory arbitrage. Economic life is socially constructed, society =
has rules, and you can make use of the rules to make money.</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is admittedly an idiosyncratic lesson to =
learn from a weird corner of the financial industry, but I kind of took awa=
y the notion that the structuring of economic entitlements is an underrated=
 part of finance, while moving capital from people who have it to people wh=
o need it and allocating risk sensibly were maybe somewhat overrated. A lot=
 of the action, it seems to me, is in the weeds of the contracts and the ru=
les, not in the broad economic ideas.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31871501.256403/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9vb=
i13YWxsLXN0cmVldC1sYXd5ZXJzLW1ha2UtbW9yZS10aGFuLWJhbmtlcnMtbm93LWFlODA3MGE3=
P21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdb9d66aa" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=
=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While bankers used to make multiples of what l=
awyers did, the lawyers have been zooming ahead, thanks to stagnant banker =
pay for all but the very top performers and changing dynamics at law firms.=
 The trend took hold well before the recent slowdown in deal making dented =
banker pay.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wall Street Journal spoke to more than 30 =
compensation experts, bankers and lawyers and reviewed pay data over more t=
han 15 years.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Managing directors who aren=E2=80=99t in high-=
ranking leadership roles at banks make an average of between $1 million and=
 $2 million most years, including bonuses often paid largely in stock, more=
 or less unchanged from where it was two decades ago.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Equity partners at top law firms, meanwhile, c=
an make around $3 million or more a year=E2=80=94more than triple what they=
 were pulling in two decades ago. An elite group of partners who bring in e=
xceptional amounts of business are earning north of $15 million at a handfu=
l of firms including Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &amp; Katz; Kirkland &amp; Ell=
is; and Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &amp; Garrison.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThings have changed,=E2=80=9D said Ma=
rk Rosen, a longtime legal recruiter. =E2=80=9CLawyer compensation has grow=
n unbelievably.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reasons for the shifting fortunes between =
the two groups are varied. No longer relegated to simply marking up contrac=
ts, today=E2=80=99s corporate lawyers are quasibankers, serving as sounding=
 boards for corporate executives as they clash with regulators or wrestle w=
ith thorny issues such as succession planning. They have also received an o=
utsize amount of work from the rise of private equity, a client base that w=
as nowhere near as active 20 years ago.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One more possible explanation here is that pri=
vate equity is to some extent a <em>substitute </em>for investment banking:=
 Twenty years ago, if you had a company and wanted to sell it, you hired an=
 investment bank, and the bank found another company that wanted to buy you=
r company and charged a fee. It was a pure brokerage model. Private equity =
(partially) replaced that with a sort of dealer model: Now, if you have a c=
ompany and want to sell it, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that you just s=
ell it to a private equity firm, who holds onto it for a bit, spruces it up=
, finds another buyer, sells it, and collects a large markup on the overall=
 transaction. Bankers are still involved, but more of the value gets captur=
ed by the private equity firm, which anyway employs a lot of successful for=
mer investment bankers. If private equity skims off the best bankers and th=
e best banking economics, of course banker pay will go down. Meanwhile the =
private equity firms still need lots of lawyers.</p>
